# Plan: Add Pagination to GET /users

## Context
The GET /users endpoint currently returns the full `users` array (15 items) as a bare JSON array. Tests expect a paginated response with `data` (the page slice) and `pagination` metadata (`page`, `limit`, `total`, `totalPages`). Out-of-range pages must return an empty `data` array (not an error). Only one file needs to change.

---

## Critical File
- **`src/routes.ts`** â€” the only file to modify (lines 7â€“9, the GET /users handler)

## Supporting Files (read-only, no changes needed)
- `src/data.ts` â€” 15 hardcoded users in memory; `users.length` is always 15
- `src/types.ts` â€” `User` interface (id, name, email, role)
- `tests/routes.test.ts` â€” 4 tests drive the exact expected behaviour

---

## Implementation Steps

### Step 1 â€” Replace the GET /users handler in `src/routes.ts`

Replace:
```typescript
// GET /users - returns all users
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  res.json(users);
});
```

With:
```typescript
// GET /users - returns paginated users
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10;

  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const start      = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(start, start + limit);  // [] when out-of-range

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

**Key design notes:**
- `parseInt(...) || 1` / `|| 10` â€” falls back to defaults when param is absent, empty, or non-numeric.
- `Array.prototype.slice` naturally returns `[]` when `start >= users.length`, satisfying the out-of-range requirement without any extra guard.
- `totalPages` uses `Math.ceil` so e.g. 15 users / 5 per page = 3 pages exactly.
- The `GET /users/:id` handler below it is **untouched**.

---

## Test Matrix (all 4 pagination tests must pass)

| Request | Expected `data.length` | `pagination` values |
|---|---|---|
| `GET /users` (no params) | 10 | page=1, limit=10, total=15, totalPages=2 |
| `GET /users?page=2&limit=10` | 5 | page=2 |
| `GET /users?limit=5` | 5 | totalPages=3 |
| `GET /users?page=100` | 0 (empty array) | page=100 |

---

## Verification
```bash
npm test
```
All 6 tests (4 pagination + 2 existing `/users/:id` tests) should pass with no changes to test files.

